#!/bin/bash

WORKSPACE_DIR=$(mktemp -d)
LOCAL_REPOSITORY_DIR=$(mktemp -d)

echo "WORKSPACE:${WORKSPACE_DIR}"
echo "LOCAL_REPOSITORY_DIR:${LOCAL_REPOSITORY_DIR}"

# Write out a workspace file referencing
# the local repository.
cat << EOF > "${WORKSPACE_DIR}/WORKSPACE"
workspace(name = "root")

local_repository(
   name = "external_001",
   path = "${LOCAL_REPOSITORY_DIR}",
)
EOF

cat << EOF > "${LOCAL_REPOSITORY_DIR}/WORKSPACE"
workspace(name = "external_001")
EOF


# Now we can make a few targets, so aquery has
# something to report. We will mirror the BUILD.bazel files

for dir in ${WORKSPACE_DIR} ${LOCAL_REPOSITORY_DIR}; do
cat << EOF > "${dir}/script1.sh"
#/bin/bash
echo "this is script 1"
EOF

cat << EOF > "${dir}/script2.sh"
#/bin/bash
echo "this is script 2"
EOF

cat << EOF > "${dir}/BUILD.bazel"
package(
   default_visibility = ["//visibility:public"],
)

sh_binary(
   name = "script1",
   srcs =["script1.sh"],
)

sh_binary(
   name = "script2",
   srcs =["script2.sh"],
)
EOF

done

(
   cd "${WORKSPACE_DIR}"

   set -x
   # Queries in the root workspace, all return success
   bazel aquery '//:script1'
   bazel aquery '//:all'
   bazel aquery '//...'

   # Now on the external repository, the "//..." will fail
   bazel aquery '@external_001//:script1'
   bazel aquery '@external_001//:all'
   bazel aquery '@external_001//...'
)

rm -rf "${WORKSPACE_DIR}"
rm -rf "${LOCAL_REPOSITORY_DIR}"

module TodCompatability
  class Railtie < Rails::Railtie
    BROKEN_INITIALIZER_NAME = 'tod.register_active_record_type'

    initializer(
      'tod_compatability.check_register_active_record',
      before: BROKEN_INITIALIZER_NAME
    ) do |app|
      tod_railtie = app.railties.find do |railtie|
        railtie.is_a?(Tod::Railtie)
      end

      break if tod_railtie.blank?

      Rails.logger.warn(
        <<~WARNING_MESSAGE
          Tod::Railtie intitializer #{BROKEN_INITIALIZER_NAME} is disabled
          due to an incompatability with Rails 4.x.
          See: https://github.com/username_1/tod/issues/61
        WARNING_MESSAGE
      )

      broken_initalizer =
        tod_railtie
        .initializers
        .find { |initializer| initializer.name == BROKEN_INITIALIZER_NAME }

      if broken_initalizer.blank?
        Rail.logger.warn(
          <<~WARNING_MESSAGE
            Tod::Railtie intitializer #{BROKEN_INITIALIZER_NAME} is not defined.
            This may mean the issue was resolved and that this code can be removed.
          WARNING_MESSAGE
        )
        break
      end

      noop = proc {}
      broken_initalizer.instance_variable_set(:@block, noop)
    end
  end
end
